ENTRY            14861   20260217   20260508   20260508       1528
SUBENT        14861001   20260217   20260508   20260508       1528
BIB                 16         63
TITLE      Measurement of a cold neutron cross section for the
           40Ca(n,alpha)37Ar reaction
AUTHOR     (Kh.A.Shah,S.T.Castro,K.D.Mathis,J.L.Lapka,
           W.S.Charlton,D.A.Haas)
REFERENCE  (J,ARI,226,112215,2025)
           #doi:10.1016/j.apradiso.2025.112215
REL-REF    (D,,D.A.Brown+,J,NDS,148,1,2018)
INSTITUTE  (1USATEX)
FACILITY   (REAC,1USATEX) 1.1MW TRIGA Mark II research reactor
           at The University of Texas.
INC-SPECT  A monoenergetic cold neutron beam a with an expected
           flux of 5.32*10**6 n/cm2/s. The exact beam energy of
           8 meV was provided by Kh.A.Shah and not listed in the
           article.
DETECTOR   (SI,HPGE) A passivated implanted planar silicon
           detector (PIPS) with a 900 mm2 active area was chosen
           because it could be manufactured with a relatively
           large detector area and was less susceptible to
           neutron damage. A portable high-purity germanium
           detector (HPGe) was placed on the side of the setup
           to conduct prompt gamma activation analysis.
SAMPLE     The sample was a 5-cmx5-cm 2N5 purity natural Ca foil
           and two of these foils were purchased. Because this
           thickness is greater than the stopping thickness of
           the alpha particles in Ca, the foil was considered
           infinitely thick. An infinitely thick foil would
           self-shield any alpha particles that were created at
           a thickness greater than 10 microm. The
           self-shielding of these alpha particles had to be
           accounted for in the total efficiency calculations. A
           3D printed sample holder was created to hold the Ca
           samples. The samples were placed in the center of the
           chamber at a 45 degree angle to face the PIPS
           detector to maximize efficiency.
METHOD     (ACTIV,ASPEC) A cross section experiment was designed
           to measure the prompt alpha particles to determine
           the existence of the thermal neutron 40Ca(n,alpha)
           37Ar cross section. The experiment was repeated five
           times and a weighted average cross section was
           calculated.
ANALYSIS   The results from the foil experiments were background
           subtracted and analyzed to calculate the cross
           section. Reaction data from both the (n,alpha) and
            (n,g) reactions was collected for the calculation.
           Authors used the (n,g) reaction to monitor the number
           of reactions occurring in the Ca foil as part of the
            (n,a) cross section calculation. When the authors
           originally did it, they didn't have any conversion
           and therefore were assuming a thermal-equivalent
           calculation.
ERR-ANALYS (DATA-ERR) Error was propagated for each cross
           section measurement using the multiplication or
           division of variables. The uncertainty came from the
           gamma-ray net peak area, the alpha particle net peak
           area, the HPGe efficiency, the PIPS efficiency, and
           the combined prompt gamma branching ratio and cross
           section.
MONITOR    ((MONIT)20-CA-40(N,G)20-CA-41,,SIG)
MONIT-REF  ((MONIT),H.D.Choi+,W,CHOI,2007) H.D.Choi etal. Database
            of Prompt Gamma Rays from Slow Neutron Capture for
           Elemental Analysis. IAEA Technical report, IAEA (2007).
STATUS     (APRVD) Approved by Kh.A.Shah on April 30, 2026.
HISTORY    (20260217C) BP
